# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cellular-automata
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] **CA**) is a discrete model of computation studied in automata theory.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] Cellular automata are also called **cellular spaces**, **tessellation automata**, **homogeneous structures**, **cellular structures**, **tessellation structures**, and **iterative arrays**.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] Cellular automata have found application in various areas, including physics, theoretical biology, and microstructure modeling.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] A cellular automaton consists of a regular grid of *cells*, each in one of a finite number of *states*, such as *on* and *off* (in contrast to a coupled map lattice).
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] The grid can be in any finite number of dimensions.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] For each cell, a set of cells called its *neighborhood* is defined relative to the specified cell.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] An initial state (time *t* = 0) is selected by assigning a state for each cell.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] A new *generation* is created (advancing *t* by 1), according to some fixed *rule* (generally, a mathematical function) that determines the new state of each cell in terms of the current state of the cell and the states of the cells in its neighborhood.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] Typically, the rule for updating the state of cells is the same for each cell and does not change over time, and is applied to the whole grid simultaneously, though exceptions are known, such as the stochastic cellular automaton and asynchronous cellular automaton.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] The concept was originally conceived in the 1940s by Stanislaw Ulam and John von Neumann while they were contemporaries at Los Alamos National Laboratory.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] While studied by some throughout the 1950s and 1960s, it was not until the 1970s and Conway's Game of Life, a two-dimensional cellular automaton, that interest in the subject expanded beyond academia.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] In the 1980s, Stephen Wolfram engaged in a systematic study of one-dimensional cellular automata, or what he calls elementary cellular automata; his research assistant Matthew Cook showed that one of these rules is Turing-complete.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] The primary classifications of cellular automata, as outlined by Wolfram, are numbered one to four.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] This last class is thought to be computationally universal, or capable of simulating a Turing machine.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] Special types of cellular automata are *reversible*, where only a single configuration leads directly to a subsequent one, and *totalistic*, in which the future value of individual cells only depends on the total value of a group of neighboring cells.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] Cellular automata can simulate a variety of real-world systems, including biological and chemical ones.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] The range-2 "cross neighborhood" includes the pink cells as well.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] One way to simulate a two-dimensional cellular automaton is with an infinite sheet of graph paper along with a set of rules for the cells to follow.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] Each square is called a "cell" and each cell has two possible states, black or white.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] The *neighborhood* of a cell is the nearby, usually adjacent, cells.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] The two most common types of neighborhoods are the *von Neumann neighborhood* and the *Moore neighborhood*.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] The former, named after the founding cellular automaton theorist, consists of the four orthogonally adjacent cells.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] The latter includes the von Neumann neighborhood as well as the four diagonally adjacent cells.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] For such a cell and its Moore neighborhood, there are 512 (= 29) possible patterns.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] For each of the 512 possible patterns, the rule table would state whether the center cell will be black or white on the next time interval.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] Conway's Game of Life is a popular version of this model.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] Another common neighborhood type is the *extended von Neumann neighborhood*, which includes the two closest cells in each orthogonal direction, for a total of eight.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] The general equation for the total number of automata possible is *k**k**s*, where *k* is the number of possible states for a cell, and *s* is the number of neighboring cells (including the cell to be calculated itself) used to determine the cell's next state.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] Thus, in the two-dimensional system with a Moore neighborhood, the total number of automata possible would be 229, or 1.34×10154.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] It is usually assumed that every cell in the universe starts in the same state, except for a finite number of cells in other states; the assignment of state values is called a *configuration*.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] More generally, it is sometimes assumed that the universe starts out covered with a periodic pattern, and only a finite number of cells violate that pattern.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] The latter assumption is common in one-dimensional cellular automata.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] Cellular automata are often simulated on a finite grid rather than an infinite one.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] In two dimensions, the universe would be a rectangle instead of an infinite plane.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] The obvious problem with finite grids is how to handle the cells on the edges.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] How they are handled will affect the values of all the cells in the grid.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] One possible method is to allow the values in those cells to remain constant.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] Another method is to define neighborhoods differently for these cells.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] One could say that they have fewer neighbors, but then one would also have to define new rules for the cells located on the edges.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] These cells are usually handled with periodic boundary conditions resulting in a *toroidal* arrangement: when one goes off the top, one comes in at the corresponding position on the bottom, and when one goes off the left, one comes in on the right.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] Universes of other dimensions are handled similarly.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] This solves boundary problems with neighborhoods, but another advantage is that it is easily programmable using modular arithmetic functions.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] For example, in a 1-dimensional cellular automaton like the examples below, the neighborhood of a cell *xit* is {*x**i*−1*t*−1, *x**i**t*−1, *x**i*+1*t*−1}, where *t* is the time step (vertical), and *i* is the index (horizontal) in one generation.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] Stanisław Ulam, while working at the Los Alamos National Laboratory in the 1940s, studied the growth of crystals, using a simple lattice network as his model.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] At the same time, John von Neumann — Ulam's colleague at Los Alamos — was working on the problem of self-replicating systems.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] Von Neumann's initial design was founded upon the notion of one robot building another robot.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] This design is known as the kinematic model.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] As he developed this design, von Neumann came to realize the great difficulty of building a self-replicating robot, and of the great cost in providing the robot with a "sea of parts" from which to build its replicant.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] Neumann wrote a paper entitled "The general and logical theory of automata" for the Hixon Symposium in 1948.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] Ulam was the one who suggested using a *discrete* system for creating a reductionist model of self-replication.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] Nils Aall Barricelli performed many of the earliest explorations of these models of artificial life.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] Ulam and von Neumann created a method for calculating liquid motion in the late 1950s.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] The driving concept of the method was to consider a liquid as a group of discrete units and calculate the motion of each based on its neighbors' behaviors.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] Thus was born the first system of cellular automata.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] Like Ulam's lattice network, von Neumann's cellular automata are two-dimensional, with his self-replicator implemented algorithmically.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] The result was a universal copier and constructor working within a cellular automaton with a small neighborhood (only those cells that touch are neighbors; for von Neumann's cellular automata, only orthogonal cells), and with 29 states per cell.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] Von Neumann gave an existence proof that a particular pattern would make endless copies of itself within the given cellular universe by designing a 200,000 cell configuration that could do so.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] This design is known as the tessellation model, and is called a von Neumann universal constructor.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] Also in the 1940s, Norbert Wiener and Arturo Rosenblueth developed a model of excitable media with some of the characteristics of a cellular automaton.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] Their specific motivation was the mathematical description of impulse conduction in cardiac systems.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] However their model is not a cellular automaton because the medium in which signals propagate is continuous, and wave fronts are curves.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] A true cellular automaton model of excitable media was developed and studied by J.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] Hastings in 1978; see Greenberg-Hastings cellular automaton.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] The original work of Wiener and Rosenblueth contains many insights and continues to be cited in modern research publications on cardiac arrhythmia and excitable systems.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] In the 1960s, cellular automata were studied as a particular type of dynamical system and the connection with the mathematical field of symbolic dynamics was established for the first time.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] Hedlund compiled many results following this point of view in what is still considered as a seminal paper for the mathematical study of cellular automata.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] The most fundamental result is the characterization in the Curtis–Hedlund–Lyndon theorem of the set of global rules of cellular automata as the set of continuous endomorphisms of shift spaces.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] Also in 1969 computer scientist Alvy Ray Smith completed a Stanford PhD dissertation on Cellular Automata Theory, the first mathematical treatment of CA as a general class of computers.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] Many papers came from this dissertation: He showed the equivalence of neighborhoods of various shapes, how to reduce a Moore to a von Neumann neighborhood or how to reduce any neighborhood to a von Neumann neighborhood.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] He proved that two-dimensional CA are computation universal, introduced 1-dimensional CA, and showed that they too are computation universal, even with simple neighborhoods.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] He showed how to subsume the complex von Neumann proof of construction universality (and hence self-reproducing machines) into a consequence of computation universality in a 1-dimensional CA.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] Intended as the introduction to the German edition of von Neumann's book on CA, he wrote a survey of the field with dozens of references to papers, by many authors in many countries over a decade or so of work, often overlooked by modern CA researchers.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] In the 1970s a two-state, two-dimensional cellular automaton named Game of Life became widely known, particularly among the early computing community.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] Any live cell with two or three live neighbours lives on to the next generation.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] Any live cell with more than three live neighbours dies, as if by overpopulation.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] Any dead cell with exactly three live neighbours becomes a live cell, as if by reproduction.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] Despite its simplicity, the system achieves an impressive diversity of behavior, fluctuating between apparent randomness and order.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] One of the most apparent features of the Game of Life is the frequent occurrence of *gliders*, arrangements of cells that essentially move themselves across the grid.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] It is possible to arrange the automaton so that the gliders interact to perform computations, and after much effort it has been shown that the Game of Life can emulate a universal Turing machine.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] It was viewed as a largely recreational topic, and little follow-up work was done outside of investigating the particularities of the Game of Life and a few related rules in the early 1970s.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] Stephen Wolfram independently began working on cellular automata in mid-1981 after considering how complex patterns seemed formed in nature in violation of the second law of thermodynamics.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] His investigations were initially spurred by a desire to model systems such as the neural networks found in brains.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] He published his first paper in *Reviews of Modern Physics* investigating *elementary cellular automata* (Rule 30 in particular) in June 1983.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] The unexpected complexity of the behavior of these simple rules led Wolfram to suspect that complexity in nature may be due to similar mechanisms.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] His investigations, however, led him to realize that cellular automata were poor at modelling neural networks.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] Additionally, during this period Wolfram formulated the concepts of intrinsic randomness and computational irreducibility, and suggested that Rule 110 may be universal—a fact proved later by Wolfram's research assistant Matthew Cook in the 1990s.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] Wolfram, in *A New Kind of Science* and several papers dating from the mid-1980s, defined four classes into which cellular automata and several other simple computational models can be divided depending on their behavior.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] While earlier studies in cellular automata tended to try to identify types of patterns for specific rules, Wolfram's classification was the first attempt to classify the rules themselves.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] These definitions are qualitative in nature and there is some room for interpretation.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] According to Wolfram, "...with almost any general classification scheme there are inevitably cases which get assigned to one class by one definition and another class by another definition.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] There have been several attempts to classify cellular automata in formally rigorous classes, inspired by Wolfram's classification.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] For instance, Culik and Yu proposed three well-defined classes (and a fourth one for the automata not matching any of these), which are sometimes called Culik–Yu classes; membership in these proved undecidable.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] Wolfram's class 2 can be partitioned into two subgroups of stable (fixed-point) and oscillating (periodic) rules.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] A cellular automaton is *reversible* if, for every current configuration of the cellular automaton, there is exactly one past configuration (preimage).
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] If one thinks of a cellular automaton as a function mapping configurations to configurations, reversibility implies that this function is bijective.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] If a cellular automaton is reversible, its time-reversed behavior can also be described as a cellular automaton; this fact is a consequence of the Curtis–Hedlund–Lyndon theorem, a topological characterization of cellular automata.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] For cellular automata in which not every configuration has a preimage, the configurations without preimages are called *Garden of Eden* patterns.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] For one-dimensional cellular automata there are known algorithms for deciding whether a rule is reversible or irreversible.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] However, for cellular automata of two or more dimensions reversibility is undecidable; that is, there is no algorithm that takes as input an automaton rule and is guaranteed to determine correctly whether the automaton is reversible.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] The proof by Jarkko Kari is related to the tiling problem by Wang tiles.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] When a 2D automata is not reversible, often the proof can be trivial as distinct patterns that map to the same state can be quite common.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] Reversible cellular automata are often used to simulate such physical phenomena as gas and fluid dynamics, since they obey the laws of thermodynamics.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] Such cellular automata have rules specially constructed to be reversible.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] Such systems have been studied by Tommaso Toffoli, Norman Margolus and others.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] Several techniques can be used to explicitly construct reversible cellular automata with known inverses.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] Two common ones are the second-order cellular automaton and the block cellular automaton, both of which involve modifying the definition of a cellular automaton in some way.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] Although such automata do not strictly satisfy the definition given above, it can be shown that they can be emulated by conventional cellular automata with sufficiently large neighborhoods and numbers of states, and can therefore be considered a subset of conventional cellular automata.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] Conversely, it has been shown that every reversible cellular automaton can be emulated by a block cellular automaton.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] A special class of cellular automata are *totalistic* cellular automata.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] The state of each cell in a totalistic cellular automaton is represented by a number (usually an integer value drawn from a finite set), and the value of a cell at time *t* depends only on the *sum* of the values of the cells in its neighborhood (possibly including the cell itself) at time *t* − 1.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] If the state of the cell at time *t* depends on both its own state and the total of its neighbors at time *t* − 1 then the cellular automaton is properly called *outer totalistic*.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] Conway's Game of Life is outer totalistic (but not totalistic), with cell values 0 and 1.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] Outer totalistic cellular automata with the same Moore neighborhood structure as Life are sometimes called life-like cellular automata.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] More generally, an *isotropic* ruleset is one that is not necessarily outer totalistic, but still has all the reflection symmetries.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] In the case of a cellular automata on a square grid, the group of symmetries is D8.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] There are many possible generalizations of the cellular automaton concept.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] One way is by using something other than a rectangular (cubic, *etc.*) grid.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] For example, if a plane is tiled with regular hexagons, those hexagons could be used as cells.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] In many cases the resulting cellular automata are equivalent to those with rectangular grids with specially designed neighborhoods and rules.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] Another variation would be to make the grid itself irregular, such as with Penrose tiles.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] Also, rules can be probabilistic rather than deterministic.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] Such cellular automata are called probabilistic cellular automata.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] A probabilistic rule gives, for each pattern at time *t*, the probabilities that the central cell will transition to each possible state at time *t* + 1.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] The neighborhood or rules could change over time or space.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] For example, initially the new state of a cell could be determined by the horizontally adjacent cells, but for the next generation the vertical cells would be used.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] In cellular automata, the new state of a cell is not affected by the new state of other cells.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] This could be changed so that, for instance, a 2 by 2 block of cells can be determined by itself and the cells adjacent to itself.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] These are like totalistic cellular automata, but instead of the rule and states being discrete (*e.g.* a table, using states {0,1,2}), continuous functions are used, and the states become continuous (usually values in [0,1]).
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] The state of a location is a finite number of real numbers.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] Certain cellular automata can yield diffusion in liquid patterns in this way.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] Continuous spatial automata have a continuum of locations.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] Time is also continuous, and the state evolves according to differential equations.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] One important example is reaction–diffusion textures, differential equations proposed by Alan Turing to explain how chemical reactions could create the stripes on zebras and spots on leopards.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] When these are approximated by cellular automata, they often yield similar patterns.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] MacLennan considers continuous spatial automata as a model of computation.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] There are known examples of continuous spatial automata, which exhibit propagating phenomena analogous to gliders in the Game of Life.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] The simplest nontrivial cellular automaton would be one-dimensional, with two possible states per cell, and a cell's neighbors defined as the adjacent cells on either side of it.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] A cell and its two neighbors form a neighborhood of 3 cells, so there are 23 = 8 possible patterns for a neighborhood.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] A rule consists of deciding, for each pattern, whether the cell will be a 1 or a 0 in the next generation.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] These 256 cellular automata are generally referred to by their Wolfram code, a standard naming convention invented by Wolfram that gives each rule a number from 0 to 255.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] A number of papers have analyzed and compared the distinct cases among the 256 cellular automata (many are trivially isomorphic).
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] The rule 30, rule 90, rule 110, and rule 184 cellular automata are particularly interesting.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] The images below show the history of rules 30 and 110 when the starting configuration consists of a 1 (at the top of each image) surrounded by 0s.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] Each row of pixels represents a generation in the history of the automaton, with *t*=0 being the top row.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] Each pixel is colored white for 0 and black for 1.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] Rule 30 exhibits *class 3* behavior, meaning even simple input patterns such as that shown lead to chaotic, seemingly random histories.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] Rule 110, like the Game of Life, exhibits what Wolfram calls *class 4* behavior, which is neither completely random nor completely repetitive.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] Localized structures appear and interact in various complicated-looking ways.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] In the course of the development of *A New Kind of Science*, as a research assistant to Wolfram in 1994, Matthew Cook proved that some of these structures were rich enough to support universality.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] This result is interesting because rule 110 is an extremely simple one-dimensional system, and difficult to engineer to perform specific behavior.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] This result therefore provides significant support for Wolfram's view that class 4 systems are inherently likely to be universal.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] Cook presented his proof at a Santa Fe Institute conference on Cellular Automata in 1998, but Wolfram blocked the proof from being included in the conference proceedings, as Wolfram did not want the proof announced before the publication of *A New Kind of Science*.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] In 2004, Cook's proof was finally published in Wolfram's journal *Complex Systems* (Vol.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] 1), over ten years after Cook came up with it.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] Rule 110 has been the basis for some of the smallest universal Turing machines.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] An elementary cellular automaton rule is specified by 8 bits, and all elementary cellular automaton rules can be considered to sit on the vertices of the 8-dimensional unit hypercube.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] This unit hypercube is the cellular automaton rule space.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] For next-nearest-neighbor cellular automata, a rule is specified by 25 = 32 bits, and the cellular automaton rule space is a 32-dimensional unit hypercube.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] A distance between two rules can be defined by the number of steps required to move from one vertex, which represents the first rule, and another vertex, representing another rule, along the edge of the hypercube.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] This rule-to-rule distance is also called the Hamming distance.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] Cellular automaton rule space allows us to ask the question concerning whether rules with similar dynamical behavior are "close" to each other.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] Graphically drawing a high dimensional hypercube on the 2-dimensional plane remains a difficult task, and one crude locator of a rule in the hypercube is the number of bit-1 in the 8-bit string for elementary rules (or 32-bit string for the next-nearest-neighbor rules).
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] Drawing the rules in different Wolfram classes in these slices of the rule space show that class 1 rules tend to have lower number of bit-1s, thus located in one region of the space, whereas class 3 rules tend to have higher proportion (50%) of bit-1s.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] For larger cellular automaton rule space, it is shown that class 4 rules are located between the class 1 and class 3 rules.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] This observation is the foundation for the phrase edge of chaos, and is reminiscent of the phase transition in thermodynamics.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] Several biological processes or phenomena can be simulated using cellular automata, which is regarded as a specific type of agent-based model in such application contexts.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] In these biological simulations, it is common for the cells of the cellular automaton to be identified with biological cells.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] Additionally, biological phenomena which require explicit modeling of the agents' velocities (for example, those involved in collective cell migration) may be modeled by cellular automata with a more complex state space and rules, such as biological lattice-gas cellular automata.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] The Belousov–Zhabotinsky reaction is a spatio-temporal chemical oscillator that can be simulated by means of a cellular automaton.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] Belousov) discovered that when a thin, homogenous layer of a mixture of malonic acid, acidified bromate, and a ceric salt were mixed together and left undisturbed, fascinating geometric patterns such as concentric circles and spirals propagate across the medium.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] In the "Computer Recreations" section of the August 1988 issue of *Scientific American*, A.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] Dewdney discussed a cellular automaton developed by Martin Gerhardt and Heike Schuster of the University of Bielefeld (Germany).
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] This automaton produces wave patterns that resemble those in the Belousov-Zhabotinsky reaction.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] Probabilistic cellular automata are used in statistical and condensed matter physics to study phenomena like fluid dynamics and phase transitions.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] The Ising model is a prototypical example, in which each cell can be in either of two states called "up" and "down", making an idealized representation of a magnet.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] By adjusting the parameters of the model, the proportion of cells being in the same state can be varied, in ways that help explicate how ferromagnets become demagnetized when heated.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] Moreover, results from studying the demagnetization phase transition can be transferred to other phase transitions, like the evaporation of a liquid into a gas; this convenient cross-applicability is known as universality.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] The phase transition in the two-dimensional Ising model and other systems in its universality class has been of particular interest, as it requires conformal field theory to understand in depth.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] Other cellular automata that have been of significance in physics include lattice gas automata, which simulate fluid flows.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] In a series of works the so-called *vicinal Cellular Automaton* (vicCA) was proposed and further developed to model the possibly unstable growth and sublimation of vicinal crystal surfaces in 1+1D.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] Besides the attachment/detachment events being encoded in the rules of the CA, the adatoms on top of the vicinal form a thin layer, and their thermal motion is modeled by a Monte Carlo module.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] A decisive step further was the transition of the model to 2+1D, where a number of different structures were obtained, referred to by the authors as "vicinal creatures"—step bunches, step meanders, nano-pillars, nanowires, etc.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] The vicCA model was extensively used by Alexey Redkov to develop a Machine Learning algorithm on top of it, significantly speeding up calculations by a factor of 105 while enabling systematic classification of the observed phenomena.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] Cellular automaton processors are physical implementations of CA concepts, which can process information computationally.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] Processing elements are arranged in a regular grid of identical cells.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] The grid is usually a square tiling, or tessellation, of two or three dimensions; other tilings are possible, but not yet used.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] Cell states are determined only by interactions with adjacent neighbor cells.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] No means exists to communicate directly with cells farther away.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] One such cellular automaton processor array configuration is the systolic array.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] Cell interaction can be via electric charge, magnetism, vibration (phonons at quantum scales), or any other physically useful means.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] This can be done in several ways so that no wires are needed between any elements.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] This is very unlike processors used in most computers today (von Neumann designs) which are divided into sections with elements that can communicate with distant elements over wires.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] Rule 30 was originally suggested as a possible block cipher for use in cryptography.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] Two-dimensional cellular automata can be used for constructing a pseudorandom number generator.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] Cellular automata have been proposed for public-key cryptography.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] The one-way function is the evolution of a finite CA whose inverse is believed to be hard to find.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] Given the rule, anyone can easily calculate future states, but it appears to be very difficult to calculate previous states.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] Cellular automata have also been applied to design error correction codes.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] Cellular automata have been used in generative music and evolutionary music composition and procedural terrain generation in video games.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] Certain types of cellular automata can be used to generate mazes.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] Two well-known such cellular automata, Maze and Mazectric, have rulestrings B3/S12345 and B3/S1234.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] In the former, this means that cells survive from one generation to the next if they have at least one and at most five neighbours.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] In the latter, this means that cells survive if they have one to four neighbours.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] If a cell has exactly three neighbours, it is born.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] It is similar to Conway's Game of Life in that patterns that do not have a living cell adjacent to 1, 4, or 5 other living cells in any generation will behave identically to it.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] However, for large patterns, it behaves very differently from Life.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] For a random starting pattern, these maze-generating cellular automata will evolve into complex mazes with well-defined walls outlining corridors.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] Mazectric, which has the rule B3/S1234 has a tendency to generate longer and straighter corridors compared with Maze, with the rule B3/S12345.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] Since these cellular automaton rules are deterministic, each maze generated is uniquely determined by its random starting pattern.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] This is a significant drawback since the mazes tend to be relatively predictable.
[src:cellular-automata/cellular-automaton] Like some of the graph-theory based methods described above, these cellular automata typically generate mazes from a single starting pattern; hence it will usually be relatively easy to find the way to the starting cell, but harder to find the way anywhere else.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] The **Game of Life**, also known as **Conway's Game of Life** (sometimes abbreviated as **CGoL**) or simply **Life**, is a cellular automaton devised by the British mathematician John Horton Conway in 1970.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] It is a zero-player game, meaning that its evolution is determined by its initial state, requiring no further input.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] One interacts with the Game of Life by creating an initial configuration and observing how it evolves in discrete time steps called generations.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] There is no limit to the number of generations (computational resources permitting) or win condition.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] The Game of Life is played on an infinite square grid, with each cell being in one of two states: live or dead.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] Cells in configurations called *patterns* evolve over generations according to the number of live and dead cells in their Moore neighborhood, that is, the eight cells in their immediate proximity.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] Patterns can be grouped into different types, such as *still lifes*, *oscillators*, and *spaceships*.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] The Game of Life was first simulated manually, with computerized simulations arriving soon afterwards.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] Nowadays, more modern programs such as Golly are used.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] These programs often do not store cells as a two-dimensional arrays, instead using algorithms such as Hashlife which represent patterns as a tree structure.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] The Game of Life has spawned a number of other cellular automata, known as Life-like cellular automata.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] Other variations may include more than two states or use a non-square grid.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] The universe of the Game of Life is an infinite, two-dimensional orthogonal grid of square *cells*, each of which is in one of two possible states, *live* or *dead* (or *populated* and *unpopulated*, respectively).
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] Every cell interacts with its eight *neighbours* (its Moore neighborhood), which are the cells that are horizontally, vertically, or diagonally adjacent.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] This makes it described by the *rulestring* B3/S23, where the numbers before the slash signify conditions for dead cells becoming alive, and the ones after it signifying survival conditions for cells that are already alive.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] The initial pattern constitutes the *seed* of the system.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] The first *generation* is created by applying the above rules simultaneously to every cell in the seed, live or dead; births and deaths occur simultaneously, and the discrete moment at which this happens is sometimes called a *tick*.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] Each generation is a *pure function* of the preceding one.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] The rules continue to be applied repeatedly to create further generations.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] In the editable widget below, one of the patterns discovered by Conway, the I-heptomino can be simulated.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] Cellular automata have their origins in the work of Stanisław Ulam and John von Neumann in the 1940s.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] Development continued through the 1950's and 1960's when, in 1968, John Horton Conway began doing experiments with a variety of different two-dimensional cellular automaton rules.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] Conway's initial goal was to define an interesting and unpredictable cellular automaton.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] According to Martin Gardner, Conway experimented with different rules, aiming for a ruleset that would allow for patterns to "apparently" grow without limit, while keeping it difficult to *prove* that any given pattern would do so.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] Moreover, some "simple initial patterns" should "grow and change for a considerable period of time" before settling into a static configuration or a repeating loop.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] Conway later wrote that the basic motivation for Life was to create a "universal" cellular automaton.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] The game made its first public appearance in the October 1970 issue of *Scientific American*, in Martin Gardner's "Mathematical Games" column, which was based on personal conversations with Conway.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] Theoretically, the Game of Life has the power of a universal Turing machine: anything that can be computed algorithmically can be computed within the Game of Life.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] The popularity of the Game of Life was helped by its coming into being at the same time as increasingly inexpensive computer access.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] The game could be run for hours on these machines, which would otherwise have remained unused at night.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] In this respect, it foreshadowed the later popularity of computer-generated fractals.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] For many, the Game of Life was simply a programming challenge: a fun way to use otherwise wasted CPU cycles.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] It developed a cult following through the 1970s and beyond; current developments have gone so far as to create theoretic emulations of computer systems within the confines of a Game of Life board.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] Many different types of patterns occur in the Game of Life, which are classified according to their behaviour.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] Common pattern types include *still lifes*, which do not change from one generation to the next; *oscillators*, which return to their initial state after a finite number of generations; and *spaceships*, which translate themselves across the grid.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] The earliest interesting patterns in the Game of Life were discovered without the use of computers.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] The simplest still lifes and oscillators were discovered while tracking the fates of various small starting configurations using graph paper, blackboards, and physical game boards, such as those used in Go.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] During this early research, Conway discovered that the R-pentomino failed to stabilize in a small number of generations.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] In fact, it takes 1103 generations to stabilize, by which time it has a population of 116 and has generated six escaping gliders; these were the first spaceships ever discovered.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] Frequently occurring examples (in that they emerge frequently from a random starting configuration of cells called *soups*) of the three aforementioned pattern types are shown below, with live cells shown in black and dead cells in white.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] *Period* refers to the number of ticks a pattern must iterate through before returning to its initial configuration.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] The *pulsar* is the most common period-3 oscillator.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] The great majority of naturally occurring oscillators have a period of 2, like the blinker and the toad, but oscillators of all periods are known to exist, and oscillators of periods 4, 8, 14, 15, 30, and a few others have been seen to arise from random initial conditions.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] Patterns which evolve for long periods before stabilizing are called *methuselahs*, the first-discovered of which was the R-pentomino.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] *Diehard* is a pattern that disappears after 130 generations.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] Starting patterns of eight or more cells can be made to die after an arbitrarily long time.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] *Acorn* takes 5,206 generations to generate 633 cells, including 13 escaped gliders.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] Conway originally conjectured that no pattern can grow indefinitely—i.e. that for any initial configuration with a finite number of living cells, the population cannot grow beyond some finite upper limit.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] In the game's original appearance in "Mathematical Games", Conway offered a prize of fifty dollars (equivalent to $415 in 2025) to the first person who could prove or disprove the conjecture before the end of 1970.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] The prize was won in November by a team from the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, led by Bill Gosper; the "Gosper glider gun" produces its first glider on the 15th generation, and another glider every 30th generation from then on.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] For many years, this glider gun was the smallest one known.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] In 2015, a gun called the "Simkin glider gun", which releases a glider every 120th generation, was discovered that has fewer live cells but which is spread out across a larger bounding box at its extremities.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] Smaller patterns were later found that also exhibit infinite growth.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] All three of the patterns shown below grow indefinitely.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] The first two create a single *block-laying switch engine*: a configuration that leaves behind two-by-two still life blocks as it translates itself across the game's universe.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] The third configuration creates two such patterns.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] The first has only ten live cells, which has been proven to be minimal.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] The second fits in a five-by-five square, and the third is only one cell high.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] Later discoveries included other *guns*, which are stationary, and which produce gliders or other spaceships; *puffer trains*, which move along leaving behind a trail of debris; and *rakes*, which move and emit spaceships.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] Gosper also constructed the first pattern with an asymptotically optimal quadratic growth rate, called a *breeder*, which worked by leaving behind a trail of guns.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] It is possible for gliders to interact with other objects in interesting ways.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] For example, if two gliders are shot at a block in a specific position, the block will move closer to the source of the gliders.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] If three gliders are shot in just the right way, the block will move farther away.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] This *sliding block memory* can be used to simulate a counter.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] It is possible to construct logic gates such as *AND*, *OR*, and *NOT* using gliders.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] It is possible to build a pattern that acts like a finite-state machine connected to two counters.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] This has the same computational power as a universal Turing machine, so the Game of Life is theoretically as powerful as any computer with unlimited memory and no time constraints; it is Turing complete.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] In fact, several different programmable computer architectures have been implemented in the Game of Life, including a pattern that simulates Tetris.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] Until the 2010s, all known spaceships could only move orthogonally or diagonally.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] Spaceships which move neither orthogonally nor diagonally are commonly referred to as *oblique spaceships*.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] Wade announced the first oblique spaceship, dubbed "Gemini", that creates a copy of itself on (5,1) further while destroying its parent.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] This pattern replicates in 34 million generations, and uses an instruction tape made of gliders oscillating between two stable configurations made of Chapman–Greene construction arms.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] These, in turn, create new copies of the pattern, and destroy the previous copy.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] In December 2015, diagonal versions of the Gemini were built.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] A more specific case is a *knightship*, a spaceship that moves two squares left for every one square it moves down (like a knight in chess), whose existence had been predicted by Elwyn Berlekamp since 1982.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] The first elementary knightship, Sir Robin, was discovered in 2018 by Adam P.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] This is the first new spaceship movement pattern for an elementary spaceship found in forty-eight years.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] "Elementary" means that it cannot be decomposed into smaller interacting patterns such as gliders and still lifes.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] A pattern can contain a collection of guns that fire gliders in such a way as to construct new objects, including copies of the original pattern.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] A *universal constructor* can be built which contains a Turing complete computer, and which can build many types of complex objects, including more copies of itself.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] On November 23, 2013, Dave Greene built the first replicator in the Game of Life that creates a complete copy of itself, including the instruction tape.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] Goucher finished his construction of the 0E0P metacell, a metacell capable of self-replication.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] This differed from previous metacells, such as the OTCA metapixel by Brice Due, which only worked with already constructed copies near them.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] The 0E0P metacell works by using construction arms to create copies that simulate the programmed rule.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] The actual simulation of the Game of Life or other Moore neighbourhood rules is done by simulating an equivalent rule using the von Neumann neighbourhood with more states.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] The name 0E0P is short for "Zero Encoded by Zero Population", which indicates that instead of a metacell being in an "off" state simulating empty space, the 0E0P metacell removes itself when the cell enters that state, leaving a blank space.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] Many starting patterns in the Game of Life eventually become a combination of still lifes, oscillators, and spaceships; other patterns may be called chaotic.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] A pattern may stay chaotic for a very long time until it eventually settles to such a combination.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] Patterns may be constructed to emulate logical gates and replicate computing components such as information storage, logical instruction sets and program storage.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] These components then can be used to construct a computer within the Game of Life.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] Therefore, the Game of Life is Turing-complete and may therefore execute arbitrary programs.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] By the halting problem it is undecidable whether an arbitrary program executed in the Game of Life would ever terminate.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] Translating back into the terms of the Game of Life, given an initial configuration pattern and a target pattern, it is also undecidable whether the target pattern will ever appear.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] Since its publication, the Game of Life has attracted much interest because of the surprising ways in which the patterns can evolve.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] It provides an example of emergence and self-organization.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] A version of Life that incorporates random fluctuations has been used in physics to study phase transitions and nonequilibrium dynamics.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] The game can also serve as a didactic analogy, used to convey the somewhat counter-intuitive notion that design and organization can spontaneously emerge in the absence of a designer.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] From most random initial patterns of living cells on the grid, observers will find the population constantly changing as the generations tick by.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] The patterns that emerge from the simple rules may be considered a form of mathematical beauty.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] Small isolated subpatterns with no initial symmetry tend to become symmetrical.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] Once this happens, the symmetry may increase in richness, but it cannot be lost unless a nearby subpattern comes close enough to disturb it.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] In a very few cases, the society eventually dies out, with all living cells vanishing, though this may not happen for a great many generations.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] Most initial patterns eventually burn out, producing either stable figures or patterns that oscillate forever between two or more states; many also produce one or more gliders or spaceships that travel indefinitely away from the initial location.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] Because of the nearest-neighbour based rules, no information can travel through the grid at a greater rate than one cell per unit time, so this velocity is said to be the cellular automaton speed of light and denoted *c*.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] Computers have been used to follow and simulate the Game of Life since it was first publicized.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] When John Conway was first investigating how various starting configurations developed, he tracked them by hand using a go board with its black and white stones.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] The first interactive Game of Life program was written in an early version of ALGOL 68C for the PDP-7 by M.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] A color version of the Game of Life was written by Ed Hall in 1976 for Cromemco microcomputers, and a display from that program filled the cover of the June 1976 issue of *Byte*.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] The advent of microcomputer-based color graphics from Cromemco has been credited with a revival of interest in the game.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] Two early implementations of the Game of Life on home computers were by Malcolm Banthorpe written in BBC BASIC.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] The first was in the January 1984 issue of *Acorn User* magazine, and Banthorpe followed this with a three-dimensional version in the May 1984 issue.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] Susan Stepney, Professor of Computer Science at the University of York, followed this up in 1988 with Life on the Line, a program that generated one-dimensional cellular automata.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] Early patterns with unknown futures, such as the R-pentomino, led computer programmers to write programs to track the evolution of patterns in the Game of Life.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] Most of the early algorithms were similar: they represented the patterns as two-dimensional arrays in computer memory.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] Typically, two arrays are used: one to hold the current generation, and one to calculate its successor.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] Often 0 and 1 represent dead and live cells, respectively.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] A nested for loop considers each element of the current array in turn, counting the live neighbours of each cell to decide whether the corresponding element of the successor array should be 0 or 1.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] For the next iteration, the arrays may swap roles so that the successor array in the last iteration becomes the current array in the next iteration, or one may copy the values of the second array into the first array then update the second array from the first array again.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] A variety of minor enhancements to this basic scheme are possible, and there are many ways to save unnecessary computation.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] A cell that did not change at the last time step, and none of whose neighbours changed, is guaranteed not to change at the current time step as well, so a program that keeps track of which areas are active can save time by not updating inactive zones.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] To save memory, the storage can be reduced to one array plus two line buffers.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] One line buffer is used to calculate the successor state for a line, then the second line buffer is used to calculate the successor state for the next line.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] The first buffer is then written to its line and freed to hold the successor state for the third line.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] If a toroidal array is used, a third buffer is needed so that the original state of the first line in the array can be saved until the last line is computed.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] In principle, the Game of Life field is infinite, but computers have finite memory.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] This leads to problems when the active area encroaches on the border of the array.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] Programmers have used several strategies to address these problems.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] The simplest strategy is to assume that every cell outside the array is dead.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] This is easy to program but leads to inaccurate results when the active area crosses the boundary.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] A more sophisticated trick is to consider the left and right edges of the field to be stitched together, and the top and bottom edges also, yielding a toroidal array.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] The result is that active areas that move across a field edge reappear at the opposite edge.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] Inaccuracy can still result if the pattern grows too large, but there are no pathological edge effects.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] Techniques of dynamic storage allocation may also be used, creating ever-larger arrays to hold growing patterns.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] The Game of Life on a finite field is sometimes explicitly studied; some implementations, such as *Golly*, support a choice of the standard infinite field, a field infinite only in one dimension, or a finite field, with a choice of topologies such as a cylinder, a torus, or a Möbius strip.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] Alternatively, programmers may abandon the notion of representing the Game of Life field with a two-dimensional array, and use a different data structure, such as a vector of coordinate pairs representing live cells.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] This allows the pattern to move about the field unhindered, as long as the population does not exceed the size of the live-coordinate array.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] The drawback is that counting live neighbours becomes a hash-table lookup or search operation, slowing down simulation speed.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] With more sophisticated data structures this problem can also be largely solved.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] For exploring large patterns at great time depths, sophisticated algorithms such as Hashlife may be useful.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] There is also a method for implementation of the Game of Life and other cellular automata using arbitrary asynchronous updates while still exactly emulating the behaviour of the synchronous game.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] Source code examples that implement the basic Game of Life scenario in various programming languages, including C, C++, Java and Python can be found at Rosetta Code.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] There are now thousands of Game of Life programs online, so a full list will not be provided here.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] The following is a small selection of programs with some special claim to notability, such as popularity or unusual features.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] Most of these programs incorporate a graphical user interface for pattern editing and simulation, the capability for simulating multiple rules including the Game of Life, and a large library of interesting patterns in the Game of Life and other cellular automaton rules.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] Since the Game of Life's inception, new, similar cellular automata have been developed.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] The standard Game of Life is symbolized in rule-string notation as B3/S23.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] A cell is born if it has exactly three neighbours, survives if it has two or three living neighbours, and dies otherwise.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] The first number, or list of numbers, is what is required for a dead cell to be born.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] The second set is the requirement for a live cell to survive to the next generation.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] Hence B6/S16 means "a cell is born if there are six neighbours, and lives on if there are either one or six neighbours".
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] Cellular automata on a two-dimensional grid that can be described in this way are known as Life-like cellular automata.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] Another common Life-like automaton, Highlife, is described by the rule B36/S23, because having six neighbours, in addition to the original game's B3/S23 rule, causes a birth.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] HighLife is best known for its frequently occurring replicators.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] Additional Life-like cellular automata exist.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] The vast majority of these 218 different rules produce universes that are either too chaotic or too desolate to be of interest, but a large subset do display interesting behaviour.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] A further generalization produces the *isotropic* rulespace, with 2102 possible cellular automaton rules (the Game of Life again being one of them).
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] These are rules that use the same square grid as the Life-like rules and the same eight-cell neighbourhood, and are likewise invariant under rotation and reflection.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] However, in isotropic rules, the positions of neighbour cells relative to each other may be taken into account in determining a cell's future state—not just the total number of those neighbours.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] Some variations on The Game of Life modify the geometry of the universe as well as the rules.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] The above variations can be thought of as a two-dimensional square, because the world is two-dimensional and laid out in a square grid.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] One-dimensional square variations, known as elementary cellular automata, and three-dimensional square variations have been developed, as have two-dimensional hexagonal and triangular variations.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] A variant using aperiodic tiling grids has also been made.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] Conway's rules may also be generalized such that instead of two states, *live* and *dead*, there are three or more.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] State transitions are then determined either by a weighting system or by a table specifying separate transition rules for each state; for example, Mirek's Cellebration's multi-coloured Rules Table and Weighted Life rule families each include sample rules equivalent to the Game of Life.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] Patterns relating to fractals and fractal systems may also be observed in certain Life-like variations.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] For example, the automaton B1/S12 generates four very close approximations to the Sierpinski triangle when applied to a single live cell.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] The Sierpinski triangle can also be observed in the Game of Life by examining the long-term growth of an infinitely long single-cell-thick line of live cells, as well as in Highlife, Seeds (B2/S), and Stephen Wolfram's Rule 90.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] Immigration is a variation that is very similar to the Game of Life, except that there are two *on* states, often expressed as two different colours.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] Whenever a new cell is born, it takes on the on state that is the majority in the three cells that gave it birth.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] This feature can be used to examine interactions between spaceships and other objects within the game.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] Another similar variation, called QuadLife, involves four different on states.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] When a new cell is born from three different on neighbours, it takes the fourth value, and otherwise, like Immigration, it takes the majority value.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] Except for the variation among on cells, both of these variations act identically to the Game of Life.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] Blob's Organism is a Shoot 'em up based on Conway's Life.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] In the game, Life continually generates on a group of cells within a "petri dish".
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] The patterns formed are smoothed and rounded to look like a growing amoeba spewing smaller ones (actually gliders).
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] Special "probes" zap the "blob" to keep it from overflowing the dish while destroying its nucleus.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] Google implemented an easter egg of the Game of Life in 2012.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] Users who search for the term are shown an implementation of the game in the search results page.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] Various musical composition techniques use the Game of Life, especially in MIDI sequencing.
[src:cellular-automata/conway-s-game-of-life] A variety of programs exist for creating sound from patterns generated in the Game of Life.
[src:cellular-automata/elementary-cellular-automaton] There is an elementary cellular automaton (rule 110, defined below) which is capable of universal computation, and as such it is one of the simplest possible models of computation.
[src:cellular-automata/elementary-cellular-automaton] There are 8 = 23 possible configurations for a cell and its two immediate neighbors.
[src:cellular-automata/elementary-cellular-automaton] The rule defining the cellular automaton must specify the resulting state for each of these possibilities so there are 256 = 223 possible elementary cellular automata.
[src:cellular-automata/elementary-cellular-automaton] Stephen Wolfram proposed a scheme, known as the Wolfram code, to assign each rule a number from 0 to 255 which has become standard.
[src:cellular-automata/elementary-cellular-automaton] Each possible current configuration is written in order, 111, 110, ..., 001, 000, and the resulting state for each of these configurations is written in the same order and interpreted as the binary representation of an integer.
[src:cellular-automata/elementary-cellular-automaton] This number is taken to be the rule number of the automaton.
[src:cellular-automata/elementary-cellular-automaton] Although there are 256 possible rules, many of these are trivially equivalent to each other up to a simple transformation of the underlying geometry.
[src:cellular-automata/elementary-cellular-automaton] The first such transformation is reflection through a vertical axis and the result of applying this transformation to a given rule is called the **mirrored rule**.
[src:cellular-automata/elementary-cellular-automaton] These rules will exhibit the same behavior up to reflection through a vertical axis, and so are equivalent in a computational sense.
[src:cellular-automata/elementary-cellular-automaton] Rules which are the same as their mirrored rule are called **amphichiral**.
[src:cellular-automata/elementary-cellular-automaton] Of the 256 elementary cellular automata, 64 are amphichiral.
[src:cellular-automata/elementary-cellular-automaton] The second such transformation is to exchange the roles of 0 and 1 in the definition.
[src:cellular-automata/elementary-cellular-automaton] The result of applying this transformation to a given rule is called the **complementary rule**.
[src:cellular-automata/elementary-cellular-automaton] There are 16 rules which are the same as their complementary rules.
[src:cellular-automata/elementary-cellular-automaton] Finally, the previous two transformations can be applied successively to a rule to obtain the mirrored complementary rule.
[src:cellular-automata/elementary-cellular-automaton] For example, the mirrored complementary rule of rule 110 is rule 193.
[src:cellular-automata/elementary-cellular-automaton] There are 16 rules which are the same as their mirrored complementary rules.
[src:cellular-automata/elementary-cellular-automaton] Of the 256 elementary cellular automata, there are 88 which are inequivalent under these transformations.
[src:cellular-automata/elementary-cellular-automaton] It turns out that reflection and complementation are automorphisms of the monoid of one-dimensional cellular automata, as they both preserve composition.
[src:cellular-automata/elementary-cellular-automaton] One method used to study these automata is to follow its history with an initial state of all 0s except for a single cell with a 1.
[src:cellular-automata/elementary-cellular-automaton] When the rule number is even (so that an input of 000 does not compute to a 1) it makes sense to interpret state at each time, *t*, as an integer expressed in binary, producing a sequence *a*(*t*) of integers.
[src:cellular-automata/elementary-cellular-automaton] In many cases these sequences have simple, closed form expressions or have a generating function with a simple form.
[src:cellular-automata/elementary-cellular-automaton] This can be obtained by taking successive rows of Pascal's triangle modulo 2 and interpreting them as integers in binary, which can be graphically represented by a Sierpinski triangle.
[src:cellular-automata/elementary-cellular-automaton] This can be obtained by taking successive rows of Pascal's triangle modulo 2 and interpreting them as integers in base 4.
[src:cellular-automata/elementary-cellular-automaton] This is simply the sequence generated by rule 60 (which is its mirror rule) multiplied by successive powers of 2.
[src:cellular-automata/elementary-cellular-automaton] Rule 110 has the perhaps surprising property that it is Turing complete, and thus capable of universal computation.
[src:cellular-automata/elementary-cellular-automaton] This can be obtained by taking the coefficients of the successive powers of (1+*x*+*x*2) modulo 2 and interpreting them as integers in binary.
[src:cellular-automata/elementary-cellular-automaton] Note: rule 252 generates the same sequence.
[src:cellular-automata/elementary-cellular-automaton] Note that rule 254 generates the same sequence.
[src:cellular-automata/elementary-cellular-automaton] These images depict space-time diagrams, in which each row of pixels shows the cells of the automaton at a single point in time, with time increasing downwards.
[src:cellular-automata/elementary-cellular-automaton] They start with an initial automaton state in which a single cell, the pixel in the center of the top row of pixels, is in state 1 and all other cells are 0.
[src:cellular-automata/elementary-cellular-automaton] A second way to investigate the behavior of these automata is to examine its history starting with a random state.
[src:cellular-automata/elementary-cellular-automaton] This behavior can be better understood in terms of Wolfram classes.
[src:cellular-automata/elementary-cellular-automaton] Wolfram gives the following examples as typical rules of each class.
[src:cellular-automata/elementary-cellular-automaton] Each computed result is placed under that result's source creating a two-dimensional representation of the system's evolution.
[src:cellular-automata/elementary-cellular-automaton] In the following gallery, this evolution from random initial conditions is shown for each of the 88 inequivalent rules.
[src:cellular-automata/elementary-cellular-automaton] Below each image is the rule number used to produce the image, and in brackets the rule numbers of equivalent rules produced by reflection or complementing are included, if they exist.
[src:cellular-automata/elementary-cellular-automaton] As mentioned above, the reflected rule would produce a reflected image, while the complementary rule would produce an image with black and white swapped.
[src:cellular-automata/elementary-cellular-automaton] In some cases the behavior of a cellular automaton is not immediately obvious.
[src:cellular-automata/elementary-cellular-automaton] For example, for Rule 62, interacting structures develop as in a Class 4.
[src:cellular-automata/elementary-cellular-automaton] But in these interactions at least one of the structures is annihilated so the automaton eventually enters a repetitive state and the cellular automaton is Class 2.
[src:cellular-automata/elementary-cellular-automaton] Rule 73 is Class 2 because any time there are two consecutive 1s surrounded by 0s, this feature is preserved in succeeding generations.
[src:cellular-automata/elementary-cellular-automaton] This effectively creates walls which block the flow of information between different parts of the array.
[src:cellular-automata/elementary-cellular-automaton] There are a finite number of possible configurations in the section between two walls so the automaton must eventually start repeating inside each section, though the period may be very long if the section is wide enough.
[src:cellular-automata/elementary-cellular-automaton] These walls will form with probability 1 for completely random initial conditions.
[src:cellular-automata/elementary-cellular-automaton] However, if the condition is added that the lengths of runs of consecutive 0s or 1s must always be odd, then the automaton displays Class 3 behavior since the walls can never form.
[src:cellular-automata/elementary-cellular-automaton] Rule 54 is Class 4 and also appears to be capable of universal computation, but has not been studied as thoroughly as Rule 110.
[src:cellular-automata/elementary-cellular-automaton] Many interacting structures have been cataloged which collectively are expected to be sufficient for universality.
[src:cellular-automata/elementary-cellular-automaton] Many elementary cellular automata are deterministically solvable, meaning that one can express the state of a given cell after n iterations starting from initial configuration $x\in \{0,1\}^{\mathbb {Z} }$ by an explicit formula.
[src:cellular-automata/elementary-cellular-automaton] Let $[F^{n}(x)]_{j}$ represent the state of cell j after n iterations or rule F .
[src:cellular-automata/elementary-cellular-automaton] Initial condition is represented by x , so that $x_{i}$ is the state of cell i in the initial configuration, $x_{i}\in \{0,1\}$ .
[src:cellular-automata/elementary-cellular-automaton] Three representative examples are shown below.
[src:cellular-automata/elementary-cellular-automaton] Deterministic solution formulae have been derived by H.
[src:cellular-automata/elementary-cellular-automaton] Using these formulae, it is possible to derive probabilities occurrence of small blocks of symbols.
[src:cellular-automata/elementary-cellular-automaton] Entries for Rule 184 or Rule 90 show examples of expressions for such probabilities.
[src:cellular-automata/rule-110] The **Rule 110 cellular automaton** (often called simply **Rule 110**) is an elementary cellular automaton with interesting behavior on the boundary between stability and chaos.
[src:cellular-automata/rule-110] In this respect, it is similar to Conway's Game of Life: like the Game of Life, Rule 110 with a particular repeating background pattern is known to be Turing complete.
[src:cellular-automata/rule-110] This implies that, in principle, any calculation or computer program can be simulated using this automaton.
[src:cellular-automata/rule-110] In an elementary cellular automaton, a one-dimensional pattern of 0s and 1s evolves according to a simple set of rules.
[src:cellular-automata/rule-110] Whether a point in the pattern will be 0 or 1 in the new generation depends on its current value, as well as on those of its two neighbors.
[src:cellular-automata/rule-110] The name "Rule 110" derives from the fact that this rule can be summarized in the binary sequence 01101110; interpreted as a binary number, this corresponds to the decimal value 110.
[src:cellular-automata/rule-110] In 2004, Matthew Cook published a proof that Rule 110 with a particular repeating background pattern is Turing complete, i.e., capable of universal computation, which Stephen Wolfram had conjectured in 1985.
[src:cellular-automata/rule-110] Cook presented his proof at the Santa Fe Institute conference CA98 before publication of Wolfram's book *A New Kind of Science*.
[src:cellular-automata/rule-110] This resulted in a legal affair based on a non-disclosure agreement with Wolfram Research.
[src:cellular-automata/rule-110] Wolfram Research blocked publication of Cook's proof for several years.
[src:cellular-automata/rule-110] Among the 88 possible unique elementary cellular automata, Rule 110 is the only one for which Turing completeness has been directly proven, although proofs for several similar rules follow as simple corollaries (e.g.
[src:cellular-automata/rule-110] Rule 124, which is the horizontal reflection of Rule 110).
[src:cellular-automata/rule-110] Rule 110 has been described as one of the simplest known Turing complete systems.
[src:cellular-automata/rule-110] Rule 110, like the Game of Life, exhibits what Wolfram calls "Class 4 behavior", which is neither completely stable nor completely chaotic.
[src:cellular-automata/rule-110] Localized structures appear and interact in complex ways.
[src:cellular-automata/rule-110] Matthew Cook proved Rule 110 capable of supporting universal computation by successively emulating cyclic tag systems, then 2-tag system, and then Turing machines.
[src:cellular-automata/rule-110] The final stage has exponential time overhead because the Turing machine's tape is encoded with a unary numeral system.
[src:cellular-automata/rule-110] Neary and Woods (2006) presented a different construction that replaces 2-tag systems with clockwise Turing machines and has polynomial overhead.
[src:cellular-automata/rule-110] Matthew Cook presented his proof of the universality of Rule 110 at a Santa Fe Institute conference, held before the publication of *A New Kind of Science*.
[src:cellular-automata/rule-110] Wolfram Research claimed that this presentation violated Cook's nondisclosure agreement with his employer, and obtained a court order excluding Cook's paper from the published conference proceedings.
[src:cellular-automata/rule-110] The existence of Cook's proof nevertheless became known.
[src:cellular-automata/rule-110] Interest in his proof stemmed not so much from its result as from its methods, specifically from the technical details of its construction.
[src:cellular-automata/rule-110] The character of Cook's proof differs considerably from the discussion of Rule 110 in *A New Kind of Science*.
[src:cellular-automata/rule-110] Cook has since written a paper setting out his complete proof.
[src:cellular-automata/rule-110] Cook proved that Rule 110 was universal (or Turing complete) by showing it was possible to use the rule to emulate another computational model, the cyclic tag system, which is known to be universal.
[src:cellular-automata/rule-110] He first isolated a number of spaceships, self-perpetuating localized patterns, that could be constructed on an infinitely repeating pattern in a Rule 110 universe.
[src:cellular-automata/rule-110] He then devised a way for combinations of these structures to interact in a manner that could be exploited for computation.
[src:cellular-automata/rule-110] The function of the universal machine in Rule 110 requires a finite number of localized patterns to be embedded within an infinitely repeating background pattern.
[src:cellular-automata/rule-110] The background pattern is fourteen cells wide and repeats itself exactly every seven iterations.
[src:cellular-automata/rule-110] Three localized patterns are of particular importance in the Rule 110 universal machine.
[src:cellular-automata/rule-110] They are shown in the image below, surrounded by the repeating background pattern.
[src:cellular-automata/rule-110] The leftmost structure shifts to the right two cells and repeats every three generations.
[src:cellular-automata/rule-110] It comprises the sequence **0001110111** surrounded by the background pattern given above, as well as two different evolutions of this sequence.
[src:cellular-automata/rule-110] In the figures, time elapses from top to bottom: the top line represents the initial state, and each following line the state at the next time.
[src:cellular-automata/rule-110] The center structure shifts left eight cells and repeats every thirty generations.
[src:cellular-automata/rule-110] It comprises the sequence **1001111** surrounded by the background pattern given above, as well as twenty-nine different evolutions of this sequence.
[src:cellular-automata/rule-110] The rightmost structure remains stationary and repeats every seven generations.
[src:cellular-automata/rule-110] It comprises the sequence **111** surrounded by the background pattern given above, as well as five different evolutions of this sequence.
[src:cellular-automata/rule-110] Below is an image showing the first two structures passing through each other without interacting other than by translation (left), and interacting to form the third structure (right).
[src:cellular-automata/rule-110] There are numerous other spaceships in Rule 110, but they do not feature as prominently in the universality proof.
[src:cellular-automata/rule-110] The initial spacing between these components is of utmost importance.
[src:cellular-automata/rule-110] In order for the cellular automaton to implement the cyclic tag system, the automaton's initial conditions must be carefully selected so that the various localized structures contained therein interact in a highly ordered way.
[src:cellular-automata/rule-110] The *data string* in the cyclic tag system is represented by a series of stationary repeating structures of the type shown above.
[src:cellular-automata/rule-110] Varying amounts of horizontal space between these structures serve to differentiate 1 symbols from 0 symbols.
[src:cellular-automata/rule-110] These symbols represent the *word* on which the cyclic tag system is operating, and the first such symbol is destroyed upon consideration of every production rule.
[src:cellular-automata/rule-110] When this leading symbol is a 1, new symbols are added to the end of the string; when it is 0, no new symbols are added.
[src:cellular-automata/rule-110] The mechanism for achieving this is described below.
[src:cellular-automata/rule-110] Entering from the right are a series of left-moving structures of the type shown above, separated by varying amounts of horizontal space.
[src:cellular-automata/rule-110] Large numbers of these structures are combined with different spacings to represent 0s and 1s in the cyclic tag system's production rules.
[src:cellular-automata/rule-110] Because the tag system's production rules are known at the time of creation of the program, and infinitely repeating, the patterns of 0s and 1s at the initial condition can be represented by an infinitely repeating string.
[src:cellular-automata/rule-110] Each production rule is separated from the next by another structure known as a *rule separator* (or *block separator*), which moves towards the left at the same rate as the encoding of the production rules.
[src:cellular-automata/rule-110] When a left-moving rule separator encounters a stationary symbol in the cyclic tag system's data string, it causes the first symbol it encounters to be destroyed.
[src:cellular-automata/rule-110] However, its subsequent behavior varies depending on whether the symbol encoded by the string had been a 0 or a 1.
[src:cellular-automata/rule-110] If a 0, the rule separator changes into a new structure which blocks the incoming production rule.
[src:cellular-automata/rule-110] This new structure is destroyed when it encounters the next rule separator.
[src:cellular-automata/rule-110] If, on the other hand, the symbol in the string was a 1, the rule separator changes into a new structure which admits the incoming production rule.
[src:cellular-automata/rule-110] Although the new structure is again destroyed when it encounters the next rule separator, it first allows a series of structures to pass through towards the left.
[src:cellular-automata/rule-110] These structures are then made to append themselves to the end of the cyclic tag system's data string.
[src:cellular-automata/rule-110] This final transformation is accomplished by means of a series of infinitely repeating, right-moving *clock pulses* in the right-moving pattern shown above.
[src:cellular-automata/rule-110] The clock pulses transform incoming left-moving 1 symbols from a production rule into stationary 1 symbols of the data string, and incoming 0 symbols from a production rule into stationary 0 symbols of the data string.
[src:cellular-automata/rule-110] The figure above is the schematic diagram of the reconstruction of a cyclic tag system in Rule 110.
[src:cellular-automata/von-neumann-cellular-automaton] Nobili cellular automaton is a variation of von Neumann's cellular automaton, augmented with the ability for confluent cells to cross signals and store information.
[src:cellular-automata/von-neumann-cellular-automaton] The former requires an extra three states, hence Nobili's cellular automaton has 32 states, rather than 29.
[src:cellular-automata/von-neumann-cellular-automaton] Hutton's cellular automaton is yet another variation, which allows a loop of data, analogous to Langton's loops, to replicate.
[src:cellular-automata/von-neumann-cellular-automaton] In general, cellular automata (CA) constitute an arrangement of **finite-state automata** (FSA) that sit in positional relationships between one another, each FSA exchanging information with those other FSAs to which it is positionally adjacent.
[src:cellular-automata/von-neumann-cellular-automaton] In von Neumann's cellular automaton, the finite state machines (or ***cells***) are arranged in a two-dimensional Cartesian grid, and interface with the surrounding four cells.
[src:cellular-automata/von-neumann-cellular-automaton] As von Neumann's cellular automaton was the first example to use this arrangement, it is known as the von Neumann neighbourhood.
[src:cellular-automata/von-neumann-cellular-automaton] The set of FSAs define a **cell space** of infinite size.
[src:cellular-automata/von-neumann-cellular-automaton] All FSAs are identical in terms of state-transition function, or rule-set.
[src:cellular-automata/von-neumann-cellular-automaton] The **neighborhood** (a grouping function) is part of the state-transition function, and defines for any cell the set of other cells upon which the state of that cell depends.
[src:cellular-automata/von-neumann-cellular-automaton] All cells make their transitions synchronously, in step with a universal "clock" as in a synchronous digital circuit.
[src:cellular-automata/von-neumann-cellular-automaton] Each FSA of the von Neumann cell space can accept any of the 29 states of the rule-set.
[src:cellular-automata/von-neumann-cellular-automaton] The rule-set is grouped into five orthogonal subsets.
[src:cellular-automata/von-neumann-cellular-automaton] Each state includes the colour of the cell in the cellular automata program Golly in (red, green, blue).
[src:cellular-automata/von-neumann-cellular-automaton] "Excited" states carry data, at the rate of one bit per state transition step.
[src:cellular-automata/von-neumann-cellular-automaton] Note that confluent states have the property of a one-cycle delay, thus effectively holding two bits of data at any given time.
[src:cellular-automata/von-neumann-cellular-automaton] The flow of bits between cells is indicated by the direction property.
[src:cellular-automata/von-neumann-cellular-automaton] Initially, much of the cell-space, the universe of the cellular automaton, is "blank", consisting of cells in the ground state **U**.
[src:cellular-automata/von-neumann-cellular-automaton] When given an input excitation from a neighboring ordinary- or special transmission state, the cell in the ground state becomes "sensitised", transitioning through a series of states before finally "resting" at a quiescent transmission or confluent state.
[src:cellular-automata/von-neumann-cellular-automaton] The choice of which destination state the cell will reach is determined by the sequence of input signals.
[src:cellular-automata/von-neumann-cellular-automaton] Therefore, the transition/sensitised states can be thought of as the nodes of a bifurcation tree leading from the ground-state to each of the quiescent transmission and confluent states.
[src:cellular-automata/wireworld] As in all cellular automata, time proceeds in discrete steps called generations (sometimes "gens" or "ticks").
[src:cellular-automata/wireworld] Wireworld uses what is called the Moore neighborhood, which means that in the rules above, neighbouring means one cell away (range value of one) in any direction, both orthogonal and diagonal.
[src:cellular-automata/wireworld] These simple rules can be used to construct logic gates (see below).
[src:cellular-automata/wireworld] Entities built within Wireworld universes include Langton's ant (allowing any Langton's ant pattern to be built within Wireworld) and the Wireworld computer, a Turing-complete computer implemented as a cellular automaton.
